# Hydra (THC Hydra)

## Overview

Hydra is an open-source password auditing and login brute-force tool used to test authentication mechanisms.

It supports numerous network protocols and services.

> Note: Hydra should only be used on systems you own or have explicit permission to test.

---

## Common Supported Protocols

- SSH
- FTP
- HTTP
- HTTPS
- Telnet
- SMB
- RDP
- MySQL
- PostgreSQL
- VNC
- POP3
- IMAP
- SMTP

---

## Basic Syntax

```bash
hydra [options] service://target
```

---

## Important Options

| Option | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| -l | Single username |
| -L | Username list |
| -p | Single password |
| -P | Password list |
| -t | Number of parallel tasks |
| -V | Verbose output |
| -f | Stop after first valid login |
| -o | Save output to a file |

---

## Example Commands

Single username with password list

```bash
hydra -l admin -P passwords.txt ssh://192.168.1.10
```

Username list and password list

```bash
hydra -L users.txt -P passwords.txt ftp://192.168.1.20
```

HTTP POST login

```bash
hydra http-post-form
```

---

## Common Use Cases

- Password auditing
- Weak password detection
- Security assessments
- Penetration testing

---

## Limitations

- Account lockout policies
- Rate limiting
- MFA authentication
- CAPTCHA protections

---

## Best Practices

- Obtain written authorization before testing.
- Use strong password policies.
- Enable account lockout.
- Implement MFA.
- Monitor authentication logs.

---

## Skills Learned

- Password auditing
- Brute-force methodology
- Authentication testing
- Login security assessment

---

## Key Takeaways

- Hydra is one of the most widely used login auditing tools.
- It supports dozens of protocols.
- Defensive controls like MFA and account lockouts significantly reduce brute-force risk.


# Compliance (TryHackMe)

## Overview

The Compliance room introduces security compliance frameworks, standards, and regulations that organizations follow to protect information and meet legal requirements.

Compliance demonstrates that an organization adheres to recognized security and privacy standards.

---

## Why Compliance Matters

- Protects sensitive information
- Meets legal requirements
- Reduces security risks
- Builds customer trust
- Avoids regulatory penalties

---

## Common Security Standards

### ISO/IEC 27001

International standard for Information Security Management Systems (ISMS).

Focuses on:

- Risk management
- Security policies
- Continuous improvement

---

### PCI DSS

Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard.

Applies to organizations that store, process, or transmit payment card information.

Objectives:

- Secure cardholder data
- Protect payment systems

---

### GDPR

General Data Protection Regulation.

Protects personal data of individuals within the European Union.

Core principles:

- Lawfulness
- Transparency
- Data minimization
- Accuracy
- Accountability

---

### HIPAA

Protects healthcare information in the United States.

Focuses on:

- Patient privacy
- Secure storage of medical records

---

### SOC 2

Framework for evaluating service organizations.

Trust Service Criteria:

- Security
- Availability
- Processing Integrity
- Confidentiality
- Privacy

---

## Compliance vs Security

| Compliance | Security |
|------------|----------|
| Meeting regulations | Protecting systems from threats |
| Follows standards | Continuous protection |
| Periodic audits | Ongoing monitoring |

Compliance does **not** automatically guarantee security.

---

## Risk Assessment

Organizations identify:

- Assets
- Threats
- Vulnerabilities
- Likelihood
- Impact

Controls are then implemented to reduce risk.

---

## Security Controls

### Administrative

- Policies
- Procedures
- Employee training

### Technical

- Firewalls
- Encryption
- MFA
- Antivirus

### Physical

- CCTV
- Access badges
- Locks
- Security guards

---

## Skills Learned

- Compliance frameworks
- Risk management
- Security controls
- Regulatory awareness

---

## Key Takeaways

- Compliance helps organizations meet regulatory requirements.
- Security and compliance work together but are not the same.
- Risk assessments drive security decisions.
- Effective compliance requires continuous monitoring and improvement.
